        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Commands like `:exit`, `:cd` or `:find` also can error with `E77: Too many file names`, we wouldn't want them to suggest `:next` instead\n\nTrue, but we can adjust the message to make sense. After all, if the user accidentally passes a glob to those commands, then a hint makes sense there too.\n\n> Would it be better to allow for multiple files in the Lua **and then** error later in `do_exedit()` ?\n\nNot sure why Lua is mentioned. Cmdline (`:edit`) is a \"DWIM\"/user interface, whereas Lua is programmatic. For programmatic purposes, glob/wildcard is already possible (`vim.glob`, etc.) and the error message UX is not very relevant. Though we have discussed a formal API (`nvim_edit`) for opening files, but that's a separate topic.\n\n\n\n",
